<h2 class="note-header">TOTAL DAILY DOSE AND DRUG INTERACTIONS OF ANTIEPILEPTICS</h2>

<div class="callout def">
    <div>Drug interactions are extremely important in antiepileptic therapy because many antiepileptic drugs induce or inhibit hepatic microsomal enzymes. This may either decrease the effect of another drug or increase toxicity.</div>
</div>

FLOWCHART: An antiepileptic drug is administered together with another drug ->
    The antiepileptic either induces or inhibits hepatic enzymes ->
    The plasma concentration of the second drug changes ->
    [Treatment failure develops | Toxicity develops]

<h2 class="note-header">PHENYTOIN</h2>

TABLE:
| Property | Details |
| Total Daily Dose | <span class="hl-green">200–400 mg</span> |

<h3>Interaction 1: Phenytoin with Oral Contraceptive Pills, Steroids, Vitamin D and Theophylline</h3>

FLOWCHART: Phenytoin induces hepatic microsomal enzymes ->
    Metabolism of oral contraceptive pills, steroids, vitamin D and theophylline increases ->
    The plasma concentration of these drugs falls ->
    Their effectiveness decreases

TABLE:
| Drug Affected by Phenytoin | Result |
| Oral contraceptive pills | Contraceptive failure may occur |
| Steroids | Effect decreases |
| Vitamin D | Vitamin D deficiency and osteomalacia may develop |
| Theophylline | Bronchodilator effect decreases |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"PHENYTOIN Pushes Pills, Prednisolone and Vitamin D Down"</div>
</div>

<h3>Interaction 2: Phenytoin with Carbamazepine</h3>

FLOWCHART: Phenytoin induces metabolism of carbamazepine ->
    Carbamazepine induces metabolism of phenytoin ->
    The plasma concentration of both drugs decreases ->
    The effectiveness of both drugs becomes less

<p><span class="hl-yellow">This is called mutual induction.</span></p>

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"Phenytoin and Carbamazepine Compete and Clear each other"</div>
</div>

<h3>Interaction 3: Chloramphenicol, Isoniazid and Warfarin with Phenytoin</h3>

FLOWCHART: Chloramphenicol, isoniazid or warfarin is given together with phenytoin ->
    Metabolism of phenytoin becomes inhibited ->
    Plasma concentration of phenytoin rises ->
    <span class="hl-red">Phenytoin toxicity develops</span>

TABLE:
| Drug Given with Phenytoin | Result |
| Chloramphenicol | Phenytoin toxicity |
| Isoniazid (INH) | Phenytoin toxicity |
| Warfarin | Phenytoin toxicity |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"CIW increases phenytoin"</div>
    <ul class="mnemonic-list">
        <li>C = Chloramphenicol</li>
        <li>I = INH</li>
        <li>W = Warfarin</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="note-header">CARBAMAZEPINE</h2>

TABLE:
| Property | Details |
| Total Daily Dose | <span class="hl-green">600–1200 mg</span> |

<h3>Interaction 1: Carbamazepine with Phenytoin, Phenobarbitone, Sodium Valproate and Oral Contraceptive Pills</h3>

FLOWCHART: Carbamazepine induces hepatic enzymes ->
    Metabolism of phenytoin, phenobarbitone, sodium valproate and oral contraceptive pills increases ->
    Plasma concentration of these drugs decreases ->
    Their therapeutic effect becomes less

TABLE:
| Drug Affected by Carbamazepine | Result |
| Phenytoin | Reduced effect |
| Phenobarbitone | Reduced effect |
| Sodium valproate | Reduced effect |
| Oral contraceptive pills | Contraceptive failure |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"CARBAMAZEPINE Clears Pills and Phenytoin"</div>
</div>

<h3>Interaction 2: INH and Erythromycin with Carbamazepine</h3>

FLOWCHART: INH or erythromycin is administered together with carbamazepine ->
    Metabolism of carbamazepine becomes inhibited ->
    Carbamazepine accumulates in the body ->
    <span class="hl-red">Carbamazepine toxicity develops</span>

TABLE:
| Drug Given with Carbamazepine | Result |
| INH | Carbamazepine toxicity |
| Erythromycin | Carbamazepine toxicity |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"IE increases carbamazepine"</div>
    <ul class="mnemonic-list">
        <li>I = INH</li>
        <li>E = Erythromycin</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="note-header">PHENOBARBITONE</h2>

TABLE:
| Property | Details |
| Total Daily Dose | <span class="hl-green">100–200 mg</span> |

<h3>Interaction of Phenobarbitone with Oral Contraceptive Pills, Warfarin, Griseofulvin and Theophylline</h3>

FLOWCHART: Phenobarbitone induces hepatic microsomal enzymes ->
    Metabolism of oral contraceptive pills, warfarin, griseofulvin and theophylline increases ->
    Their plasma concentration decreases ->
    Their effect becomes weaker

TABLE:
| Drug Affected by Phenobarbitone | Result |
| Oral contraceptive pills | Failure of contraception |
| Warfarin | Reduced anticoagulant effect |
| Griseofulvin | Reduced antifungal effect |
| Theophylline | Reduced bronchodilator effect |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"PHENOBARBITONE Pushes Women, Worms and Wheeze drugs away"</div>
    <ul class="mnemonic-list">
        <li>W = Warfarin</li>
        <li>W = Women pills (oral contraceptives)</li>
        <li>W = Wheeze drug (theophylline)</li>
        <li>W = Worm/fungal drug (griseofulvin)</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="note-header">ETHOSUXIMIDE</h2>

TABLE:
| Property | Details |
| Total Daily Dose | <span class="hl-green">500–1500 mg</span> |

<h3>Interaction of Ethosuximide with Valproate</h3>

FLOWCHART: Valproate is given together with ethosuximide ->
    Valproate inhibits metabolism of ethosuximide ->
    Plasma concentration of ethosuximide increases ->
    <span class="hl-red">Risk of ethosuximide toxicity increases</span>

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"Valproate Values Ethosuximide too much"</div>
</div>

<h2 class="note-header">SODIUM VALPROATE</h2>

TABLE:
| Property | Details |
| Total Daily Dose | <span class="hl-green">1500–2000 mg</span> |

<h3>Interaction 1: Sodium Valproate with Phenytoin</h3>

FLOWCHART: Sodium valproate is given together with phenytoin ->
    Valproate displaces phenytoin from plasma protein binding sites ->
    Free phenytoin concentration rises ->
    <span class="hl-red">Phenytoin toxicity develops</span>

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"Valproate pushes Phenytoin free"</div>
</div>

<h3>Interaction 2: Sodium Valproate with Phenobarbitone</h3>

FLOWCHART: Valproate inhibits the degradation of phenobarbitone ->
    Plasma concentration of phenobarbitone increases ->
    <span class="hl-red">Phenobarbitone toxicity may occur</span>

<h3>Interaction 3: Sodium Valproate with Carbamazepine</h3>

FLOWCHART: Sodium valproate and carbamazepine are administered together ->
    The incidence of teratogenicity increases ->
    Risk to the fetus becomes greater during pregnancy

TABLE:
| Drug Combination | Important Result |
| Valproate + Phenytoin | Phenytoin toxicity |
| Valproate + Phenobarbitone | Phenobarbitone toxicity |
| Valproate + Carbamazepine | Increased teratogenicity |

<div class="mnemonic-box">
    <div class="mnemonic-title">Mnemonic</div>
    <div class="mnemonic-text">"Valproate causes 3 P problems"</div>
    <ul class="mnemonic-list">
        <li>P = Pushes phenytoin from proteins</li>
        <li>P = Potentiates phenobarbitone</li>
        <li>P = Pregnancy risk increases with carbamazepine</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 class="note-header">SUMMARY TABLE</h2>

TABLE:
| Drug | Total Daily Dose | Important Interaction |
| Phenytoin | <span class="hl-green">200–400 mg</span> | Reduces effect of OC pills, steroids, vitamin D and theophylline |
| Carbamazepine | <span class="hl-green">600–1200 mg</span> | Reduces effect of phenytoin, phenobarbitone, valproate and OC pills |
| Phenobarbitone | <span class="hl-green">100–200 mg</span> | Reduces effect of OC pills, warfarin, griseofulvin and theophylline |
| Ethosuximide | <span class="hl-green">500–1500 mg</span> | Valproate increases its concentration |
| Sodium valproate | <span class="hl-green">1500–2000 mg</span> | Causes phenytoin and phenobarbitone toxicity |



